The paper deals with the problem of providing explanations for missing tuples in query results, which is a fundamental problem in database systems. The use of ontologies to provide high-level and meaningful reasons for why a tuple is missing from the result of a query suggests that the paper belongs to the sub-category of databases (cs.DB). The paper also proposes algorithms for computing most-general explanations for why-not questions, which involves reasoning about concepts and subsumption relationships, suggesting that it may also belong to the sub-categories of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and logic in computer science (cs.LO). The paper also discusses the use of ontologies for information retrieval (cs.IR) and the use of description logics (DL) for efficient concept subsumption checking, suggesting that it may also belong to the sub-category of DL (cs.DL).
